text:
Hololive D&D would be very nice.
Please consider playing even off stream, just for fun with friends.
The fact that the game is well known and yet few people know how they can start playing is a thing that Wizards of the coast should consider.
It is a epic game full of good memories for me.
Hope more people get started into the game, for my perspective the game fits really well in the live format, all the expectation of rolling die and waiting for the result is very entertaining.

For those who not know, imagine playing in a fantasy world, like in the Lord of the rings or some other fantastic world. One person at the table is the GM (Game master) and the others generally play as 1 character each (there is no real limit about max players, but over 7 starts to get fuss). The GM is responsible of making the adventure, building fun and bad NPC's, epic (or so not) adventures and various dilemas. The limit is your imagination, the book is there to support the GM not to limit him.

Give a try with your friends and you will not regret, if the fantasy setting of D&D isn't for you there are a bunch of others TTRPG settings that will fit.

text: It would be a long journey. She would need to make tough decisions as killer and get better at the controls and tracking survivors. She can't just never tunnel and camp and slug; while the killer shouldn't do those things all the time, there are instances where they're the best thing to do. Plus, she would need to learn how to mind game and loop because those are more common at red ranks. The survivors at low ranks for the most part just run forward without thinking about what tiles to look for and how to use them efficiently. Gen defense perks, efficiency and a mind set on defending gens would also help her win
author: @epiksar

text:
It‚Äôll also come with the choice of what killer will be the best. With each having their own abilities, it all comes down to map pressure and how good they‚Äôre in the chase like Nurse or Hillbilly.

The problem with killers is that some of their abilities are just too weak to even get kills. Legion is a pretty good example. Some killers are really good and easy to play like Oni (from what I think), but I‚Äôve always had problems playing Nurse. 

She‚Äôs one of the best killers in the game yet one of the hardest killers to learn and master. It‚Äôs all about reads. You got to be constantly thinking what the survivors are going to do next. Does this David have dead hard, does Bill have unbreakable, will Jake fake vault the window or does he go back and vault the window again, does this Meg double back a lot. Every single information is essential. Most of Nurse‚Äôs add-one screw her over. You just have to learn your mistakes in order to get better at her. It‚Äôs not a pick up and play killer, but a pick up and learn killer.

It‚Äôs usually why I don‚Äôt like being in red ranks. I don‚Äôt want to play a certain killer in order to just win. I just want to have fun. I‚Äôm sure Gura will understand once she reaches that point in her journey.

If you read this far, then I appreciate it.

Thank you for joining my Ted Talk.

having just finished my first-ever campaign as a non-DM player tonight, they would need to pick a friggin' dang good DM to wrangle all the new players.
